{
  "doc_id": "30767",
  "text": "Several surgeons recommend immediate open anatomic reduction of both the ulna fracture and the radial head dislocation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Delpont et al. reported good long term outcomes of the open anatomic restoration even one year after the injury [CITATION_5] . Nakamura et al. [CITATION_6] performed the open reduction of the radial head combined with ulnar osteotomy and annular ligament reconstruction in 22 pediatric cases. Their retrospective evaluation were showed that if the open reduction was performed when the patient was less than 20 years of age or within 3 years after the injury, good long term clinical and radiographic outcomes would be expected [CITATION_7] . In our case, we preferred a similar technique as soon as the injury was diagnosed, which resulted satisfactory functional and radiographic outcomes.",
